	affiliations = {Universitat de Barcelona, Barcelona, Spain},
	abstract = {Objective: this article aims to analyze whether the actions implemented by the Peruvian State ensure the right of access to justice for individuals who communicate in indigenous or native languages. The hypothesis holds that these actions remain insufficient, thus requiring regulatory and technological reforms aligned with national and international standards, as well as soft law. Method: the research adopted a qualitative, documentary approach, grounded in an interpretive perspective and developed under a non-experimental design. Normative, jurisprudential, and doctrinal sources were analyzed, along with the application of a comparative method using the cases of Spain and Paraguay. Results: the findings showed that, although there have been normative, political, and administrative advances, these are not sufficient to guarantee a truly multilingual justice system, due to structural barriers, a shortage of interpreters, a lack of dissemination of legal norms in native languages, and the limited linguistic training of justice operators. Conclusions: the study proposes a regulatory reform to guarantee the use of all indigenous languages in the courts, free access to translation services, the mandatory incorporation of bilingual judges in multilingual regions, and the use of technology to enhance linguistic inclusion in hearings, jurisprudence, and judicial user services. The effective recognition of linguistic rights is presented as an imperative for a truly inclusive justice system. © 2025 Elsevier B.V., All rights reserved.},
