	affiliations = {Helsingin Yliopisto, Helsinki, Finland; The Education University of Hong Kong, Hong Kong, Hong Kong},
	abstract = {This chapter introduces the promises, pitfalls and possibilities of AI in intercultural communication education and research (ICER). Drawing inspiration from Chekhov’s (1903) The Cherry Orchard, the editors reflect on the tensions between technological disruption and “traditional” paradigms, questioning whether AI could flatten intercultural complexities or serve as, e.g., a reflexive and decolonial tool. While AI offers unparalleled efficiencies in, e.g., language learning, virtual exchanges and intercultural knowledge construction and dissemination, many seem to argue that it also risks reinforcing biases, essentialist narratives and Western-centric epistemologies. Through diverse scholarly perspectives, the book chapters explore ethical, pedagogical and epistemological dimensions of AI and ICER, advocating for intentional and justice-centred engagements that preserve agency and plurality. In so doing, chapter contributors employ innovative methodologies such as AI-human dialogues, mock interviews and Indigenous knowledge reclamation to interrogate AI’s dual potential as both a reproducer of dominant ideologies and a catalyst for critical and reflexive interculturality. This introductory chapter calls for considering AI as an “intercultural companion”, urging educators, researchers and students to explore its paradoxes with reflexivity and ethical caution. © 2025 Elsevier B.V., All rights reserved.},
