	url = {https://www.scopus.com/inward/record.uri?eid=2-s2.0-105018177233&doi=10.1080%2F14724049.2025.2567367&partnerID=40&md5=11d39db49ce2d7d8cfa496062dde5aa4},
	affiliations = {Universidad Autónoma de Bucaramanga, Bucaramanga, Colombia},
	abstract = {A technology-enabled, sustainable model of nature-based tourism can be developed in Río de Oro, a small municipality in the Colombian Caribbean, by leveraging its ecological, cultural, and digital assets. Using a mixed-methods approach that combined document analysis, field visits, and participatory workshops, the study identified key conditions shaping tourism opportunities in the region. Río de Oro’s ecosystems–including tropical dry and premontane humid forests–along with landmarks such as Las Marcelinas waterfall and El Fin del Mundo viewpoint provide a strong basis for ecotourism. However, limited tourism infrastructure and mobile internet connectivity restrict access and visitor engagement. Tools such as augmented reality (AR) and artificial intelligence (AI), when aligned with local knowledge and values, were recognized as effective for enhancing environmental education, promoting cultural heritage, and supporting community-led strategies. The participatory design process revealed strong community interest in using digital technologies for storytelling, conservation messaging, and route planning. By linking ecological stewardship with digital inclusion, the study shows how small municipalities can design inclusive, conservation-oriented tourism pathways that strengthen biodiversity protection and local identity. Nature-based tourism, in this context, emerges as a vehicle for territorial re-signification, ecological resilience, and digitally mediated rural development. © 2025 Elsevier B.V., All rights reserved.},
