	affiliations = {IPB University, Department of Forest Resources Conservation and Ecotourism, Bogor, Indonesia},
	abstract = {Enggano Island, a small and outermost island of Indonesia, possesses high biodiversity with notable endemism and risk of extinction. This loss not only affects biodiversity but also impacts the traditional knowledge systems passed down through the Enggano language. The Enggano language plays a crucial role in forming an ethnobotanical classification system, where native speakers contribute to the naming and grouping edible plant species. This study aims to identify edible plant species utilized by the indigenous Enggano community and reveal the ethnobotanical knowledge they employ. The research methods include participatory observation, freelisting, and in-depth interviews with 40 indigenous Enggano informants. The findings identified 150 edible plant species categorized through four naming mechanisms: morphology (48), ecology (13), utility (18), and quality (10) of species. However, 76 species (46%) remain unidentified due to limited information on local names that are gradually fading. Revitalizing the Enggano language is essential as an effort to support plant conservation by strengthening language and local knowledge. © 2025 Elsevier B.V., All rights reserved.},
