	affiliations = {Pak-Austria Fachhochschule: Institute of Applied Sciences and Technology, Department of Biological and Health Sciences, Haripur, Pakistan},
	abstract = {This chapter delves into the regulatory frameworks governing the production, marketing, and distribution of herbal products. With a growing global demand for enhanced quality of life, health, and social well-being, there is an increasing preference for natural remedies. However, the quality, efficacy, and safety of these products can be compromised without proper regulation. Key aspects discussed in this chapter include safety assessments, evidence of efficacy, and adverse event reporting, underscoring the importance of robust scientific evaluation and monitoring. The chapter also covers labeling requirements, emphasizing the need for accurate and substantiated health claims and the inclusion of essential product information to inform both consumers and regulators. The regulatory requirements for herbal products across major regions, including Europe, America, and Asia, are examined, highlighting the differences in classification from dietary supplements to traditional medicines and their implications for manufacturers. Challenges due to irregularities and the lack of proper international standards are also explored. Post-market surveillance mechanisms, including monitoring, product recalls, and handling consumer complaints, are addressed to illustrate the ongoing regulatory responsibilities of manufacturers. The chapter acknowledges the role of traditional use evidence and compliance with pharmacopeial standards, offering insights into how historical data can support regulatory approval. Additionally, it addresses the integration of traditional knowledge with current research and advanced technologies in quality control. Key topics discussed include good manufacturing practices (GMP) and the roles of regulatory authorities such as the Food and Drug Administration, the World Health Organization, and the European Medicines Agency. Through case studies and an analysis of the current regulatory setup, the chapter aims to guide stakeholders in navigating the complex regulatory environment, fostering innovation, and safeguarding public health in the intricate field of herbal medicine. © 2025 Elsevier B.V., All rights reserved.},
