	abstract = {This paper analyzes the local names of animals from a multidisciplinary perspective. Through the ethnographic survey and scientific literature review conducted during 2021/2023 it has been possible to register the traditional and ethnozoological knowledge of the region. It has obtained 392 zoonyms of 183 animals (180 identified species and three groups undetermined still). The estimated results of the analysis indicate that 59.71 % of the zoonyms have Basque lexemes, prefixes, or suffixes. Likewise, the article exposes how different elements of them are shared among the unlike animals studied and the 84.7 % of these animals have multiplicity of local names. In addition, after the ethnographic classification of them, it has been possible to verify that the categories of physiozoonym and onomazoonym are the most representative. The study concludes with an assessment of the evolution of the loss or conservation of these common names, considering the local anthropological and zoological contextualization. © 2025 Elsevier B.V., All rights reserved.},
