	affiliations = {Vellore Institute of Technology, Vellore, India},
	abstract = {The soil fertility is declining slowly with an increasing population which is not recognizable with naked eye like disasters such as floods and droughts. Therefore, it does not get the as much as attention it requires. Soil pollution emerging as an important threat to soil function for which specific accelerated actions are needed, to maintain nutrient balance, offset the effects of soil pollution, salinization, and soil erosion, and sustains overall soil quality. The physical, chemical, and mineralogical composition of soil is greatly influenced by the processes like weathering, erosion, transportation, and deposition. Thus, an understanding of the processes that controls the behavior of the source material is essential for qualitative as well as quantitative characterization of soil. The sustainable management of soil is directly or indirectly crucial for mineral resource management, nutrient balance, crop production, environmental sustainability, and on human health. Thus, soil heath status study not only will provide an early indication of the problems associated with soil nutrient surplus or a deficit but also it helps in crop yields management. This chapter provides a depth knowledge about the relation between the soil health and nutrient flow by identifying the root cause from the system, i.e., at the field level, farm level, and regional level. This process is done with the help of traditional knowledge and high-resolution data like multispectral data, hyperspectral data, and geographic information system (GIS) approach for spatial variability-based methods proposed in this study. This chapter’s main focus is to manage the spatial variability of soils and nutrients availability by using the techniques like machine learning (ML) and the internet of things (IoT). Digital information extraction method can be broadly used in agricultural field to help farmers to increase productivity, pest management and land sustainability practices. Agriculture can be integrated into urban and peri-urban areas which can contribute to the self-sufficient neighborhood while, reconnecting people with nature and consumption with production. This chapter delivers a comprehensive knowledge of the current and potential applications of modern technologies, its challenges, and possible solutions implementations for soil fertility. © 2025 Elsevier B.V., All rights reserved.},
