	affiliations = {Bhole and Associates Mumbai, Mumbai, India},
	abstract = {Abstract discusses advanced local construction techniques which still exist in certain districts of Himachal Pradesh, with a detailed case study of Fort Chehni, situated in Kullu district. In India, many indigenous building practices have kept changing over times, but few have remained unchanged to date. One such place where these practices are still kept alive is known as the “Abode of Gods” i.e. Himachal Pradesh. Himachal forms an interesting mixture of spiritual values, superstitions, socio-cultural customs and celebrated tales. The history of any architecture is not only a classification of buildings in isolation but definitely a history of the region, state and the country as a whole. All customs, skills, traditions, communities and people are clearly reflected in various forms. Himachal Pradesh falls under seismic zone IV and V. To counter these natural forces, the local residents have devised local ways of constructing buildings that are earthquake resistant, traditionally called KATH-KUNNI method of construction. The Kath-Kunni technology uses modest but intelligent principles which optimize the use of the locally available materials to come up with advanced earthquake-resistant technology in high seismic zone areas of Shimla, Kullu, Mandi and Kinnaur districts. This traditional science of construction has been transferred through hereditary knowledge systems of master masons. These systems are very much still in practice. This style of architecture is not only seen in Temples, Forts and Palaces but also in residences. With the passage of time and unsustainable growth taking place, this earthquake-resistant architecture is in need of urgent attention. The whole study is not made in separation, but in relation to the social, economic, and cultural background of the people of a given place. This paper is a modest attempt, spread over a period of seventeen years, in understanding, documenting and analyzing this indigenous earthquake-resistant construction technology. © 2025 Elsevier B.V., All rights reserved.},
	author_keywords = {Earthquake resistant; Hereditary; Kath-kunni; Urgent attention; Vernacular},
